      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">A 6-month-old girl presents with developing cataracts, and an inability to track objects visually. Urine tests are positive for reducing sugars but negative for glucose. Which enzyme deficiency is most likely present in this patient?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q7632017",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 29998,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. D)&nbsp; Galactokinase</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">This clinical picture is <strong>classic for galactokinase deficiency</strong>, a milder form of <strong>galactosemia</strong>, and presents primarily with:</span></p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Cataracts</strong> (due to galactitol accumulation in the lens)</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Positive urine test for reducing sugars</strong> (specifically <strong>galactose</strong>, not glucose)</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Usually <strong>no liver dysfunction</strong> or severe systemic involvement</span></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Biochemical mechanism:</strong></span></p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Galactokinase</strong> is the enzyme responsible for converting <strong>galactose to galactose-1-phosphate</strong>.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">In its deficiency, <strong>galactose accumulates</strong> and is <strong>shunted to galactitol</strong> by <strong>aldose reductase</strong>, especially in tissues like the lens → leads to <strong>osmotic damage and cataracts</strong>.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>No galactose-1-phosphate accumulation</strong> → hence <strong>no hepatotoxicity or severe neurological symptoms</strong> (as seen in classic galactosemia).</span></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Other Options:</strong></span></p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A. Aldolase B</strong> – Deficiency causes <strong>Hereditary Fructose Intolerance</strong>, leading to <strong>hypoglycemia</strong>, <strong>vomiting</strong>, and <strong>hepatomegaly</strong> upon <strong>fructose ingestion</strong>. <strong>Cataracts not a feature</strong>.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B. Fructokinase</strong> – Causes <strong>Essential Fructosuria</strong>, a benign condition. No systemic effects or cataracts.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C. Galactose-1-phosphate uridylyl transferase</strong> – Deficiency causes <strong>classic galactosemia</strong>, which includes:</span><ul style=\"list-style-type:circle;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Liver dysfunction</strong></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Neurological damage</strong></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Cataracts</strong></span></li></ul></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">This child has isolated early cataracts with galactosuria and no liver signs — more consistent with <strong>galactokinase deficiency</strong>.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Educational Objective:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Distinguish between <strong>types of galactose metabolism disorders</strong>:</span></p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Galactokinase deficiency</strong>: Early-onset <strong>cataracts</strong>, <strong>galactosuria</strong>, mild/no systemic symptoms.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Classic galactosemia (GALT deficiency)</strong>: <strong>Severe symptoms</strong> including <strong>hepatomegaly</strong>, <strong>vomiting</strong>, <strong>jaundice</strong>, and <strong>cataracts</strong>.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Both cause reducing substances in urine</strong>, but galactokinase deficiency is <strong>less severe and lacks liver involvement</strong>.</span></li></ul>",
