      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B) A as well as R are right, and R is a correct explanation of A</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Galactosemia </strong>is a <strong>metabolic disorder</strong> that results from an <strong>inability to metabolize galactose</strong> properly, typically due to a<strong> deficiency </strong>in one of the enzymes involved in the <strong>Leloir pathway</strong>, such as<strong> galactose-1-phosphate uridylyltransferase</strong>. Despite adhering to a <strong>galactose-free diet</strong>, individuals with <strong>galactosemia,</strong> including <strong>nursing mothers</strong>, can produce <strong>lactose in breast milk </strong>because the <strong>mammary gland </strong>can <strong>synthesize galactose from glucose </strong>through the<strong> epimerization of UDP-glucose to UDP-galactose.</strong> This<strong> UDP-galactose </strong>can then be used to <strong>synthesize lactose, </strong>the main <strong>sugar in milk</strong>, ensuring that <strong>lactation</strong> is <strong>not impaired </strong>in women with <strong>galactosemia</strong> who are on a <strong>galactose-free diet.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">&nbsp;<u>Explanation:</u></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. A is right but R is a wrong statement:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> This option is<strong> incorrect</strong> because <strong>both</strong> the <strong>assertion</strong> and the <strong>reasoning are correct,</strong> and the<strong> reasoning</strong> provides a<strong> valid explanation for the assertion.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. A is wrong, but R is a right statement:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> This option is<strong> incorrect </strong>because the <strong>assertion is indeed correct;</strong> <strong>nursing mothers</strong> with<strong> classic galactosemia</strong> on a<strong> galactose-free die</strong>t can produce <strong>lactose in breast milk </strong>due to the <strong>body&#39;s ability to synthesize galactose</strong> from <strong>glucose.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. A and R both are wrong:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> This option is <strong>incorrect</strong> as <strong>both the assertion </strong>and the <strong>reasoning are correct</strong> and<strong> logically</strong> <strong>consistent.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\">&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Galactose</strong> can be produced from a<strong> glucose metabolite by epimerization.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Uridine diphosphate (UDP)</strong> <strong>glucose</strong> is converted to <strong>UDP-galactose </strong>by <strong>UDP hexose 4- epimerase</strong>, thereby providing the appropriate form of <strong>galactose for lactose synthesis.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></span></u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Harper 30/e: p 155, 203, 205.</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-IN\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></strong></span></span></p>",
