      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. A) Galactosemia </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Galactosemia</strong> is due to <strong>deficiency</strong> of enzyme <strong>galactose-1-phosphate uridyl transferase. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Autosomal Recessive inheritance.</span></span></span></strong></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Due to the<strong> block </strong>in this enzyme &rarr; <strong>galactose-1- phosphate</strong> accumulates in liver &rarr; thus <strong>inhibiting galactokinase</strong> and <strong>glycogen phosphorylase </strong>&rarr;<strong> Hypoglycemia </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Galactose-1-phosphate </strong>gets deposited in <strong>renal tubules &rarr; tubular damage </strong>&rarr; <strong>generalized amino aciduria</strong>. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Bilirubin </strong>uptake and<strong> conjugation is reduced </strong>&rarr; <strong>increased unconjugated bilirubin </strong>level in blood </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Free galactose </strong>accumulates &rarr; <strong>galactosemia &rarr; galactosuria</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Clinical features: <strong>congenital cataract (oil drop cataract), enlargement of liver, jaundice, and severe mental retardation.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B. Hereditary Fructose Intolerance:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>Fructosemia&nbsp;</strong>- due to<strong> defect</strong> in <strong>Aldolase-B </strong>&rarr; <strong>fructose-1-phosphate</strong> in the diet of infants <strong>cannot </strong>be metabolized &rarr; its <strong>accumulation</strong> and <strong>inhibition of glycogen phosphorylase</strong> &rarr; accumulation of<strong> glycogen in liver </strong>and <strong>hypoglycaemia.</strong> History of <strong>aversion to sweets</strong> and <strong>history of vomiting </strong>after <strong>drinking fruit juices</strong>. C/F- <strong>Vomiting, loss of appetite,</strong> <strong>hepatomegaly and jaundice</strong>.<strong> Fructose</strong> excreted in<strong> urine</strong> gives a <strong>positive Benedict&rsquo;s test.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\">&nbsp;<strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Latent diabetes mellitus:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> They have a<strong> slow </strong>progression of <strong>autoimmune beta cell failure</strong> with<strong> C/F</strong> similar to<strong> DM.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D.&nbsp; Crigler-Najjar Syndrome:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>defective conjugation</strong> due to <strong>deficiency of UDP glucuronyl transferase</strong> &rarr;<strong> Unconjugated</strong> <strong>bilirubin &gt;&gt;20 mg/dl </strong>&rarr; <strong>kernicterus.</strong> History of <strong>persistent jaundice since birth</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective: </span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Galactosemia</strong> is a <strong>genetic disorder</strong> characterized by the<strong> inability to metabolize galactose</strong> properly <strong>due to a deficiency</strong> in one of the <strong>enzymes</strong> involved in <strong>its metabolic pathway,</strong> most commonly<strong> galactose-1-phosphate uridyltransferase.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Harper 30/e:&nbsp; p 155, 204</span></strong></span></span></p>",
