      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A woman presents to the emergency room reporting episodes of diarrhea triggered by the consumption of dairy products. This symptom is suggestive of lactose intolerance, a condition where the body lacks sufficient lactase enzyme to digest lactose, the primary sugar in milk and dairy products. Based on this information, which of the following dairy products might she be able to tolerate better compared to the others?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q6987732",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 29999,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. A) Yogurt&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A: </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Lactose intolerance </strong>is due to<strong> deficiency of the enzyme galactosidase </strong>or<strong> lactase </strong>in the<strong> intestinal mucosa</strong> leads to <strong>failure</strong> in <strong>metabolism of lactose</strong>, the <strong>primary sugar in milk and milk products</strong> to <strong>monosaccharides, galactose and glucose</strong>. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The <strong>undigested lactose</strong> passes into the <strong>colon </strong>&rarr; metabolized by <strong>resident bacteria into CO2, H2, and H2O</strong> &rarr; resulting in C/F such as <strong>bloating, flatulence, abdominal cramping, and frothy diarrhoea. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Treatment:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> <strong>avoidance</strong> of<strong> dairy products</strong> containing<strong> lactose</strong>. Persons with<strong> lactose intolerance </strong>can tolerate <strong>yogurt </strong>and <strong>acidophilus milk better</strong> than <strong>other dairy products</strong> as the <strong>lactose</strong> in these <strong>fermented </strong>products are utilized for production of <strong>lactic acid.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Other Options:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B. Skimmed milk:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Skimmed milk contains a<strong> similar amount</strong> of<strong> lactose</strong> to <strong>whole milk </strong>and can still cause <strong>symptoms </strong>in individuals with <strong>lactose intolerance.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Condensed milk:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Condensed milk has a <strong>high lactose content</strong> due to the <strong>removal of water.</strong> It is <strong>highly </strong>likely to cause <strong>symptoms </strong>in individuals with<strong> lactose intolerance.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. Ice cream:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Ice cream typically contains<strong> high levels of lactose and fat</strong>, which can <strong>exacerbate gastrointestinal symptoms</strong> in individuals with <strong>lactose intolerance.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Yogurt </strong>is often<strong> better tolerated</strong> by those with <strong>lactose intolerance</strong> due to<strong> probiotics aiding lactose digestion, </strong>whereas<strong> skimmed milk,</strong> <strong>condensed milk, and ice cream</strong>, with their <strong>higher lactose content</strong>, are <strong>more</strong> likely to cause<strong> intolerance symptoms.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Maurice Shils, Modern Nutrition in Health and Disease, 10th edition, page 1523</span></strong></span></span></p>",
